<paragraph id="42A65CAF2850C5BD988CDA26026314D7" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
Australia, Western Australia, Peak Charles, 10 Jan. 1982, parasitic on 
<taxonomicName id="25159520C1CB1E30C3A8E0C1329F2FEA" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Oxylobium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Fabales" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2BBF2A72CE1ACF3A82F38E72DBD69C05" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Oxylobium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis id="C5DE0FC6729F39410CAA0FEEB5D20351" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">B. D. Dell 8216</emphasis>
(G, MO).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="06CEC78F141EFBF114636B5AD2995AED" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis id="5F72A5E8D07AD26F4B553CFBE5410DBB" bold="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">
<pageBreakToken id="4B1265F6C263F4D8AFC9FAD9700486C1" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" start="start">Note</pageBreakToken>
:
</emphasis>
Tepals orange to red, in 3 whorls. Growing in young stems of 
<taxonomicName id="90CFD7B7234A0B1BB7E3B5174AF9B2B2" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Gastrolobium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F8092A5E1F88BEFC7F87B39BD2FFDCE1" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">Gastrolobium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="5DDC0BE80EA394ECBF7F6F71BDAC80F2" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Oxylobium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Fabales" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="821BF725F76A27114CCA9F0C4ECC15A8" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">Oxylobium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in Western Australia (
<figureCitation id="7EEE15F4238248EF46319900B2917DDC" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Geographic distribution of Apodanthaceae based on label information from 785 herbarium collections." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10621" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">Figs 2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="5DC472CC53FF806605BFDFE83B8218A0" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Phylogenetic relationships among the hosts of Apodanthaceae (legume relationships from Wojciechowski et al. 2006) and among the species of Apodanthaceae (from Bellot and Renner in review). Identical colors link parasite species and their host (s) and are also used in Figure 2. Dashed lines represent associations with rarely reported hosts; hosts in bold are the most common ones." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10622" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">3</figureCitation>
, see 
<bibRefCitation id="9A7D6D35A0869DE6F7218BD0A58B85E7" author="Thiele, KR" journalOrPublisher="Nuytsia" pageId="12" pageNumber="53" pagination="273 - 284" refId="B16" refString="Thiele, KR, Wylie, SJ, Maccarone, L, Hollick, P, McComb, JA, 2008. Pilostyles coccoidea (Apodanthaceae), a new species from Western Australia described from morphological and molecular evidence. Nuytsia 18: 273 - 284" title="Pilostyles coccoidea (Apodanthaceae), a new species from Western Australia described from morphological and molecular evidence." volume="18" year="2008">Thiele et al. 2008</bibRefCitation>
for pictures of flowers).
</paragraph>
